Prediction the letter B

To warm up, start by predicting whether or not the letter is B. First, create a new variable called IsB in your dataset, which takes value Yes if the letter is B, and No if the letter is not B. Then randomly split your dataset into a training set and a testing set, putting 50% of the data in each set.

The with function creates a new logical object which takes value TRUE if the letter in the dataset is B and FALSE otherwise. This variable is added to the original dataset using the cbind function. After that the dataset is splitted into a train and a test set of the same dimension since the split ratio condition is set to a half.

Letters <- read.csv("D:/Universit/Data Science/Decision Model/Assignment2/Letters.csv")
isB = with(Letters, Letter=="B")
Letters = cbind(Letters, isB)

set.seed(1234)
spl = sample.split(Letters$isB, SplitRatio = 0.50)
trainB = subset(Letters, spl==TRUE)
testB = subset(Letters, spl==FALSE)

Before building models, let us consider a baseline method that always predicts the most frequent outcome, which is not B. What is the accuracy of this baseline method on the test set?

First of all we need to check which is the most frequent outcome on the train dataset; in order to do that, a simple table function can be used to determinate if the TRUE values are the most frequent or viceversa.

table(trainB$isB)
## 
## FALSE  TRUE 
##  1175   383

From the output is clear that most of the outcomes areFALSE, indeed with a baseline method that always predict the most frequent outcome, all the \(1558\) observation in the test set will be predicted as FALSE. To check which is the accuracy of this method its required to run once again the table function but this time on the test dataset: as it was just said, this method will predict all the observations as false, so the accuracy will be the number of FALSE values in the test set (which are the correct predictions) divided by the number of rows.

baselinePredB = table(testB$isB)
baselineAccB = baselinePredB[[1]] / nrow(testB)
baselineAccB
## [1] 0.754172

The baselineAcc was computed in a tricky way: the table function gives as output a table where its elements can be accessed using the squared brackets. Since the header (FALSE and TRUE) is by default inside the table, using a single bracket it results in having both the numbers of FALSE or TRUE outcome along with the header. R still allows mathematical opertations with those elements, but in order to have just the single value withtout the header, another square bracket is needed to get the number. Finally the accuracy can be computed using the formula which has been already explained and the results is \(0.745\).

Build a CART tree to predict whether or not a letter is a B, using the training set to build your model. Remember to not use the variable Letter as one of the independent variables in the model, as this is related to what we are trying to predict! Select reasonable parameter values for the model, and justify your parameter choices. What is the accuracy of this CART model on the test set?

Formula = isB ~ Xbox + Ybox + Width + Height + Onpix + Xbar + Ybar + X2bar + Y2bar + XYbar + X2Ybar + XY2bar + Xedge + XedgeYcor + Yedge + YedgeXcor

minbucket = seq(5, 20, by=1)
accVect = NULL

for(i in minbucket){
  TreeB = rpart(formula = Formula, method="class", data=trainB, control=rpart.control(minbucket=i))
  predictionB = predict(TreeB, newdata=testB, type="class")
  matrixB = table(testB$isB, predictionB)
  treeBAcc = (matrixB[1] + matrixB[4]) / nrow(testB)
  accVect = c(accVect, treeBAcc) 
  }

To decide which is the better parameter for the CART model, we start with taking in consideration only the minbucket, a parameter that determinates the minimum number of observations in terminal nodes. First of all a formula variable is created containing all the variables of the dataset but Letter and isB (which is the object of the prediction). A tree is created on training dataset and consequentely a prediction is made using that model on test set. A confusion matrix is computed with the table function between the original data inside the test set and its predictions. The output is a 2x2 matrix and to compute the accuracy is just necessary to sum the elements on the main diagonal and divide by the number of observations. Since the model can have pretty different results depending on which parameters are chosen, this operation is repeated several times with a different number of minimum observations in terminal node. To achive this, a vector was created using the seq funciont; in particular this vector contains every number from \(5\) to \(20\) and at each step each number is passed as parameter in the Trees function. The lower bound was set to \(5\) since a lower value would have meant that basically some ad hoc splits for the observations, meanwhile the upper limit of \(20\) is a reasonable choice considering the dimension of the dataset. An empty vector is created to store of the accuracies. To evaluate which is the optimal parameter to choose, which maximize the accuracy, a plot is a useful tool for this task. According to the description of the package, the cp parameter is \(0.01\) and minsplit is three times the minibucket parameter.

plot(x=minbucket, y=accVect, col=1, lwd=2, xlab='Minimum observation in terminal nodes', ylab='Accuracy', type="l")

The plot looks pretty weird, it does not increase or decrease monotonically, but it shows how accuracy depends on which parameter of minbucket is set. An evolution of the cycle is implemented down below: in this case there are two for cycles the outer changes the value of the complexity parameter and the inner one is the same as before.

par(mfrow=c(2,2))
cplist = seq(0.004, 0.01, by=0.002)

for(j in cplist){
  accVect = NULL
  
  for(i in minbucket){
    
    TreeB = rpart(formula = Formula, method="class", data=trainB, control=rpart.control(minbucket=i, cp=j))
    predictionB = predict(TreeB, newdata=testB, type="class")
    matrixB = table(testB$isB, predictionB)
    treeBAcc = (matrixB[1] + matrixB[4]) / nrow(testB)
    accVect = c(accVect, treeBAcc) 
    
  }
  plot(x=minbucket, y=accVect, col=1, lwd=2, xlab='Minimum observation in terminal nodes', ylab='Accuracy', type="l", main=paste('Complexity parameter:', j))
}

The command par(mfrow=c(2,2)) allows to plot 4 graph in once for a better comparison. On the bottom right theres the original plot showed before, in this one the accuracy is lower the the two others on the first line, and its a quite obvious results since the tree accepts some splits that permit to gain even a smaller improvment for accuracy than the two on the bottom. Since the dataset is not big and the computational time is not an issue, the selected tree have as parameters \(`minbucket`=5\) and \(`cp`=0.004\), and its accuracy is

TreeB = rpart(formula = Formula, method="class", data=trainB, control=rpart.control(minbucket=5, cp=0.004))
predictionB = predict(TreeB, newdata=testB, type="class")
matrixB = table(testB$isB, predictionB)
(matrixB[1] + matrixB[4]) / nrow(testB)
## [1] 0.936457

The best tree looks like this:

fancyRpartPlot(TreeB, palettes=c("Greys", "Oranges"), sub = "Best decision tree")

Now, build a random forest model to predict whether or not the letter is a B. Again, select reasonable parameter values for the model, and justify your parameter choices. What is the accuracy of the model on the test set?

Once again a double for cycle is implemented to check which set of parameters gives the best accuracy.

set.seed(1234)
par(mfrow=c(2,2))

trainB$isB = as.factor(trainB$isB)

ntreeList = seq(100, 400, by=100)
nodesizeList = seq(10, 50, by=2)

for(i in ntreeList){
  accVect = NULL
  
  for (j in nodesizeList){
    RFB = randomForest(formula=Formula, data=trainB, ntree=i, nodesize=j)
    predictionBRF = predict(RFB, newdata=testB) 
    matrixBRF =table(testB$isB, predictionBRF)
    accBRF = (matrixBRF[1] + matrixBRF[4]) / nrow(testB)
    accVect = c(accVect, accBRF) 
  }
  
  plot(x=nodesizeList, y=accVect, col=1, lwd=2, xlab='Minimum observation in terminal nodes', ylab='Accuracy', type="l", main=paste('Trees grown', i))
}

Overall the accuracy of the random forest is higher, and this is an expected result. Again a lower nodesize means a better accuracy with basically the same value with \(10\) observations at minimum in the final nodes while computing \(200\) and \(400\) trees. In these two cases we check the exact value of the accuracy

tempVect = c(200, 400)

for(val in  tempVect){
  RFB = randomForest(formula=Formula, data=trainB, ntree=val, nodesize=10)
  predictionBRF = predict(RFB, newdata=testB) 
  matrixBRF = table(testB$isB, predictionBRF)
  print((matrixBRF[1] + matrixBRF[4]) / nrow(testB))
}
## [1] 0.9730424
## [1] 0.9762516

The accuracy achived with \(400\) is the highest. The only possible drawback in choosing \(400\) instead of \(200\) trees is about the computational time, but with a fixed value of nodesize it takes just a few seconds and indeed its not a problem at all.

Compare the accuracy of your CART and Random Forest models. Which one performs better? For this application, do you think interpretability or accuracy is more important?

Obviously with the random forest we get a better accuracy since its the combination of more trees and not a single one. The accuracy is more important than the interpretability for two reasons: the first one is that only someone whos really into this field could understand why Yedge is the first variable to split and what does it mean. The second reason is that this data were manually distorted for the classification task, hence reaching the maximum accuracy should be the main goal.

Building a more general predictor

In a multi-class classification problem, a simple baseline model is to predict the most frequent class of all of the options for every observation. For this problem, what does the baseline method predict, and what is the baseline accuracy on the testing set? Do you think this simple baseline method is a useful benchmark for this problem? Why or why not?

The code is like the previous one made for the letter B in the first request.

set.seed(1234)
spl = sample.split(Letters$Letter, SplitRatio = 0.50)
train = subset(Letters, spl==TRUE)
test = subset(Letters, spl==FALSE)

table(train$Letter)
## 
##   A   B   P   R 
## 394 383 402 379

Basically all the letters are almost evenly equal.

baselinePred = table(test$Letter)
baselineAcc = baselinePred[[3]] /nrow(test)
baselineAcc
## [1] 0.2573813

The accuracy with a baseline method is just \(0.2574\) which is way lower than the one achived by the first baseline method with just the letter B and definitely not suitble for a prediction. Usually the baseline method is never a good choice, theres always some, even easy and simple method, which is better than that one; in this particular case since the letters ratio is almost the same, probably its the worst possible method.

Now build a classification tree to predict Letter, using the training set to build your model. (Remember not to use the variable IsB in the model, as this is related to what we are trying to predict!) Select reasonable parameter values and justify your parameter choices. What is the test set accuracy of your CART model? (HINT: When you are computing the test set accuracy using a classification matrix, you want to add everything on the main diagonal and divide by the total number of observations in the test set.)

newFormula = Letter ~ Xbox + Ybox + Width + Height + Onpix + Xbar + Ybar + X2bar + Y2bar + XYbar + X2Ybar + XY2bar + Xedge + XedgeYcor + Yedge + YedgeXcor

Tree = rpart(formula = newFormula, method="class", data=train, control=rpart.control(minbucket=5, cp=0.004))
predictionTree = predict(Tree, newdata=test, type="class")
matrixTree = table(test$Letter, predictionTree)
matrixTree
##    predictionTree
##       A   B   P   R
##   A 365  10   0  20
##   B   4 330  11  38
##   P   0  17 384   0
##   R   5  28   7 339
TreeAcc = sum(diag(matrixTree))/ nrow(test)
TreeAcc
## [1] 0.9101412

The first tree built is the best obtained in the previous step. At first glance it looks a very good model: even if now the task is to predict 4 different outcomes and not only B or not B, its accuracy is still very high. To check for other possible, maybe better, models, the same for cycles are run once again.

par(mfrow=c(2,2))
cplist = seq(0.004, 0.01, by=0.002)

for(j in cplist){
  accVect = NULL
  
  for(i in minbucket){
    
    Tree = rpart(formula = newFormula, method="class", data=train, control=rpart.control(minbucket=i, cp=j))
    predictionTree = predict(Tree, newdata=test, type="class")
    matrixTree = table(test$Letter, predictionTree)
    TreeAcc = sum(diag(matrixTree))/ nrow(test)
    accVect = c(accVect, TreeAcc) 
    
  }
  plot(x=minbucket, y=accVect, col=1, lwd=2, xlab='Minimum observation in terminal nodes', ylab='Accuracy', type="l", main=paste('Complexity parameter:', j))
}

In this case the difference between both the minbucket and cp values is really relevant: growing with the minimum number of observations in the terminal nodes leads to a fast decrease of accuracy and the four plot looks pretty different with just a small increase of the complexity. If there were some doubts before on which was the best model, here the trend looks pretty clear: a more specific model is inarguably better than anything else. A comparison between the two trees, which have the same parameters, is made below by plotting them:

par(mfrow=c(1,2))

BTree = rpart(formula=Formula, method="class", data=train, control=rpart.control(minbucket=5, cp=0.004))
Tree = rpart(formula=newFormula, method="class", data=train, control=rpart.control(minbucket=5, cp=0.004))
fancyRpartPlot(BTree, palettes=c("Greys", "Oranges"), sub = "Best decision tree (letter B)")
